esult": {"media_key": "3_2062947578652856320"}}, "media_url_https": "https://pbs.twimg.com/media/HKEP5I_bEAA66WO.jpg", "original_info": {"focus_rects": [{"h": 609, "w": 1088, "x": 0, "y": 0}, {"h": 944, "w": 944, "x": 144, "y": 0}, {"h": 944, "w": 828, "x": 260, "y": 0}, {"h": 944, "w": 472, "x": 443, "y": 0}, {"h": 944, "w": 1088, "x": 0, "y": 0}], "height": 944, "width": 1088}, "sizes": {"large": {"h": 944, "resize": "fit", "w": 1088}, "medium": {"h": 944, "resize": "fit", "w": 1088}, "small": {"h": 590, "resize": "fit", "w": 680}, "thumb": {"h": 150, "resize": "crop", "w": 150}}, "type": "photo", "url": "https://t.co/nvT7eUp152"}]}, "favorite_count": 0, "favorited": false, "full_text": "Researchers at Monash University have developed a tiny chip that could help pave the way for computers that process information using light instead of electricity. Published in the journal Nature Photonics, the study demonstrates a nanoscale device capable of generating, https://t.co/nvT7eUp152", "id_str": "2062947584742920575", "is_quote_status": false, "lang": "en", "possibly_sensitive": false, "possibly_sensitive_editable": true, "quote_count": 0, "reply_count": 0, "retweet_count": 0, "retweeted": false, "user_id_str": "728853567298134016"}, "note_tweet": {"is_expandable": true, "note_tweet_results": {"result": {"entity_set": {"hashtags": [{"indices": [1346, 1351], "text": "Chip"}, {"indices": [1352, 1364], "text": "Information"}, {"indices": [1365, 1371], "text": "Light"}, {"indices": [1372, 1390], "text": "TechInvestigation"}, {"indices": [1391, 1405], "text": "valleytronics"}], "symbols": [], "timestamps": [], "urls": [], "user_mentions": []}, "id": "Tm90ZVR3ZWV0OjIwNjI5NDc1ODQ1ODM1MzY2NDA=", "text": "Researchers at Monash University have developed a tiny chip that could help pave the way for computers that process information using light instead of electricity. Published in the journal Nature Photonics, the study demonstrates a nanoscale device capable of generating, controlling and reading light-based signals on a single platform. The breakthrough uses an emerging technology called valleytronics, which relies on quantum properties in advanced materials to encode information. Researchers say the innovation could lead to faster computing, lower energy consumption and more efficient communication systems in the future.

Investigadores de la Universidad Monash desarrollaron un diminuto chip que podría ayudar a abrir el camino hacia computadoras capaces de procesar información utilizando luz en lugar de electricidad. Publicado en la revista Nature Photonics, el estudio demuestra un dispositivo a escala nanométrica capaz de generar, controlar y leer señales basadas en luz en una sola plataforma. El avance utiliza una tecnología emergente conocida como valleytrónica, que aprovecha propiedades cuánticas de materiales avanzados para codificar información. Los investigadores afirman que la innovación podría conducir a una computación más rápida, un menor consumo de energía y sistemas de comunicación más eficientes en el futuro.

#Chip #Information #Light #TechInvestigation #valleytronics"}}}, "rest_id": "2062947584742920575", "source": "<a href="http://twitter.com/download/iphone" rel="nofollow">Twitter for iPhone</a>", "unmention_data": {}, "views": {"count": "19", "state": "EnabledWithCount"}}

